<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Dwarven combine<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.44)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11684'>Ross "Nuxxy" Done</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11684&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 10, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I posted this at Decipher and was told to post it here. So here you go.<br>
<br>
I like dwarves. Not specifically in TCG, but in general. That&#39;s why I play them in TCG. I don&#39;t build decks just because they are the most potent around and will win tournements. I build them because I want to enjoy playing them. Which is why I have never used ARV. Or Galadriel&#39;s Mirror. I&#39;ll get there one day, but for the mo&#39; I&#39;m trying decks which I don&#39;t see being played. Makes for far easier trading, for one thing. ;-)<br>
<br>
Dwarven decks seem to fit that description, because most people seem to view them with a bad taste in their mouths. What I want to do here is outline a few thoughts on dwarves, and strategic reasons why I think they&#39;re viable (with added thoughts on the RotEL expansion).<br>
<br>
I&#39;ve heard it said that Dwarves are only good against Moria. I disagree. I think they&#39;re good against all Orcs. Yes, a lot of their cardshimmer Moria specifically, but a lot hit Orcs specifically. I don&#39;t know if anyone is playing an Isengard Orc deck yet. They are going to be mean, with their easy intergration with Uruk-hai and already existing Isengard cards. And the same home site as Moria. But I think Dwarves will possibly be the stronger against them than anyone else. Because their focus is on Regroup actions and limited overwhelm (they&#39;ll never be up to Moria&#39;s standards). What&#39;s the best way to stop their regroup abilities (especially now with ARV errata&#39;d)? Wound them. But they have Trapped and Alone to cancel damage bonuses from weapons. And exerting Aragorn with his Bow or the Greenleaf may not be the best idea, with the regroup wounding. Anyway, with enough twilight, the Isengard Shaman can prevent that (their Response can be anytime). And the Warrior or Spies of Saruman could kill it altogether.<br>
And Dwarves? Gimli is native <b>damage+1</b> and Lord of Moria makes each Dwarf <b>damage+1</b>. And neither are affected by trapped and alone. That extra damage could be critically important against some of the Orcs (Smith, Warrior, Overseer), and with Let Them Come, if the Dwarves win (I wouldn&#39;t bet against it) you can discard the Orcs. Immunity to the Trees Are Strong.<br>
Also, Dwarves are one of the few races that can get by without Allies. Which is good, because the Uruk Raider and Tower Assassin combination is painful - I&#39;ve had to face it alot.<br>
Against Sauron Orcs they are good as well, but mostly because of their conditions which hit Orcs specifically.<br>
<br>
Just a quickie on Fror. He is so nice. Native 8 against Uruk-hai. Plus a Dwarven Axe for no cost, with the discard card bonus (every now and again it will toss the Balrog or Witch King). If you face a lot of Uruk meta, I&#39;d recommend trying to find a way to add him to your deck. 10 strength beats a lot of Uruk-hai, and 7 strength will beat most small Orcs.<br>
<br>
But against Sauron in general, Dwarves can be not so good. Condition removal is one of their weaknesses, so You Bring Great Evil, Blade Tips and Black Breaths hurt. For a second reason, which is that Dwarves other main problem is their lack of healing. No sanctuary and they die very quickly. I know that from experience too. More on that later.<br>
And yes, they are very reliant on conditions. Which I wouldn&#39;t change. I would just add some way to recycle conditions if/when they are discarded, which Storm of Argument does to a degree. Would like something else too. Just to shuffle them back into the draw deck. It hits harder than you&#39;d think. Because Dwarven decks tend to be big. Which is not a problem in itself. Most conditions and weapons you can play immediately for almost no cost. What they really need is card drawing mechanisms, which is why the Book of Mazarbul is such a nice addition. Plus it&#39;s a possession, so it doesn&#39;t fall when you come up against Saruman&#39;s Power, and it&#39;s a Tale to pump Gloin. IMHO by far the best RotEL Dwarven card.<br>
<br>
Last week, someone said Gimli is bad because:<br>
>&quot;It&#39;s much easier to get Aragorn to strength 10 base than it is to get Gimli there. Gimli + his Axe + Bracers + Hand Axe = 10 strength, Aragorn + Sword = +10 strength with 4 vitality and the ability to either go <b>defender+1</b>, heal a companion, or remove 2 twilight before moving. This is why Gondor is more viable than Dwarvers, combined with Athelas.&quot;<br>
I&#39;m not trying to diss you, but I don&#39;t think that was a bit of an unfair comparison. Show me one other companion who does match up to AraGOD. And it&#39;s not as bad as you make out.<br>
If you have to play Aragorn, you want his card, a Ranger Sword, and an Armor, right? Only 3 cards, true, but look at the twilight -> 4+2+1=7. Even if he removes 2, it&#39;s still 5.<br>
Now Gimli. You need a Gimli card, a Dwarven Axe, a Hand Axe, Dwarven Bracers, Gimli&#39;s Helm and an Endurance of Dwarves. 6 cards is a lot. But his twilight? -> 2+0+0+1+0+1=4. And you also get a strength 10 vitality 4 companion. Now forgetting the character&#39;s card text abilities, how do they match up? Aragorn is a ranger. Gimli is <b>damage+1</b>. Both good. Ranger Sword has no extra abilities, but the dwarven axe will discard a card from the draw deck when Gimli wins. He can toss the hand axe to add to the archery. He can toss the bracers to prevent a wound. Or he can toss the Helm to prevent all wounds. He can toss the Endurance to go +1. He&#39;s still not Aragorn, but he ain&#39;t bad. And Aragorn can only go to 5 vitality, where Gimli can go to 7. With Son of Gloin you could pump his strength by 12.<br>
Yes, it takes more cards. But that&#39;s a weakness I&#39;ve already pointed to. You have to have a good card drawing mechanism, and condition removal.<br>
<br>
Which brings me to my next point. I do think that dwarves perform better with another companion from another culture. Who? There&#39;s the question. Elves allow Shoulder to Shoulder. Aragorn is Aragorn, and no more need be said.<br>
<br>
But the two I&#39;m really interested to try is Gandalf and Boromir. I think the new Boromir will go nicely. Just need his possessions. Blade of Gondor. His Cloak, which can toss all those nasty weather conditions. His Shield, which can make him a severe fighting force. He can use Athelas, and other Gondor healers. And his Horn, which if Thrarin has the +4 strength possessions, will bring him into battle as a strength 11 menace, with 1 life extra. I still think the best use of Thrarin is as a pumped-up pain who keeps coming back, with Elrond to heal him.<br>
<br>
The Mines Gandalf would also be nice. He draws a card and isn&#39;t affected by the rule of 4. He allows you to play the old Elrond, who allows you to heal Mini-Uber-Thrarin, and heal Grimir to recycle events, and exert to draw yet another card. Gandalf has some allies who would always be nice. And no one is as good at card cycling. Also, Gandalf&#39;s Cart can be so nice for all those multiple Dwarven possessions.<br>
The problem I used to have with Gandalf is that although Sleeps are deadly, if you&#39;re playing a Dwarven deck, they&#39;re not such a good idea, because it&#39;d be stupid to toss all your hard-working Dwarven conditions. But RotEL makes Gandalf such a better proposition. Narya can remove burdens, which Dwarves haven&#39;t been able to do. Betrayal of Isengard is a Saruman killer, and stackable twilight removal. Deep in Thought is the new Sleep - but it leaves your conditions intact, just the thing for Dwarves. And Unknown Perils can help in a pinch. All this besides all Gandalf&#39;s previous pluses.<br>
<br>
Just one thing about Gandalf. Deep in Thought and Unknown Perils require 4 twilight in the pool before being played. Shoulder to Shoulder can do that. But I have yet to figure out an efficient way to add twilight during the Maneuver phase. Maybe because it&#39;s not exactly efficient. And you wouldn&#39;t exactly want to do it during the fellowship phase. &quot;Oh look! The rare Saruman and 5 <b>fierce</b> Uruk-hai. GULP!&quot;<br>
<br>
One other thing about Dwarves. They do so well against Moria, but ironically they do well with them too. Because they need fast-cycling minions. Whenever I play Uruk-hai or Sauron with Dwarves I get a shadow hand clog. Not a good thing for a large deck. Moria does well not only with cycling extra cards, but also cycling quickly through a large deck.<br>
<br>
Plus a large deck gives some protection against discard decks...<br>
<br>
That&#39;s all for now. Make any comments you feel. &#39;Twas all just opinion, and I will likely be wrong on some points by some people&#39;s view. Debate away. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3856&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
